2. What is mounting in Linux?
 ðŸ‘‰ Mounting attaches a filesystem to a directory.

3. How do you check inode usage?
 ðŸ‘‰ Use df -i to view inode utilization.

4. What is an inode in Linux?
 ðŸ‘‰ Stores file metadata like permissions, owner, size â€” not filename or data.

5. Temporary vs permanent mount?
 ðŸ‘‰ Temporary mounts disappear after reboot; permanent mounts persist via /etc/fstab.


6. What is /etc/fstab used for?
 ðŸ‘‰ Defines filesystems that auto-mount at boot.

7. Block storage vs file storage?
 ðŸ‘‰ Block = raw disk; File = shared filesystem.

8. What happens when inode usage reaches 100%?
 ðŸ‘‰ No new files can be created, even if disk space is free.

9. What is LVM?
 ðŸ‘‰ Logical Volume Manager enables resizing volumes without downtime.

10. How do you extend disk space without downtime?
 ðŸ‘‰ Extend the LVM logical volume and resize the filesystem online.
 

âœ¨ Memory Shortcut
Swap = Disk extends RAM
Mount = Attach filesystem
Check inode = df -i
Temp mount = Lost after reboot
/etc/fstab = Auto-mount
Block = Raw, File = Shared
Inode full = No new files
LVM = Resize without downtime
Extend disk = LVM + resize fs
